Load Data¶

The data covers weekly sales, price, display and feature information for three brands of beer for the supermarket chain Dominicks over 227 weeks.

Retailer margin and wholesale price for each brand is also included.

In [6]:
data = pd.read_excel(f"{DATA_FOLDER}/01_raw/beer_data_chicago_Dominicks.xlsx", index_col='Week ')

Add unit sales

The SCAN*PRO model estimates unit sales rather than \$ sales. Therefore we need to create a new feature which is the estimated unit sales of each beer brand. This can be created by dividing sales ($) (SALESBRAND*) by the average price in the week (PRICEBRAND*) and rounding to the nearest integer.

In [7]:
brand_sales_cols = ['SALESBRAND1','SALESBRAND2','SALESBRAND3']
brand_price_cols = ['PRICEBRAND1','PRICEBRAND2','PRICEBRAND3']


#calculate units (round to nearest integer)
for s,p in zip(brand_sales_cols,brand_price_cols):
    data[f"UNITSBRAND{s[-1]}"] = (data[s]/data[p]).astype(int)

Add timeseries dates

The data is a time series. Currently the weeks are expressed as a incrementing series from 1 to 227. In the literature it is stated that the dataset begins in June 1989. It will be assumed that the data starts from week 1 (starting on a Sunday) of June 1989. Therefore the index will be converted to the actual dates and new column will be added to the dataset which describes the month of the year (this will be important for incorporating seasonality into the model).

In [8]:
# convert index to datetime
data.index = pd.date_range(start='1989/06/01', periods=len(data), freq='W')
data['month'] = data.index.month_name()

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Dataset characteristics¶

The main features of the dataset available for modelling include (Srinivasan et. al, 2002):

  • PRICEBRAND*: the average price of the beer brand during the week
  • display_brand*: the percentage of stock keeping units which were put on display
  • FEATUREBRAND*: the percentage of stock keeping units which were 'featured' during the week
  • REATAILERMARGINBRAND*: the percentage profit (margin) the retailer made on the sale of each product
  • SALESBRAND*: the sales in dollars (\$)
  • WHOLESALEPRICE*: the wholesale price of the product
  • UNITSBRAND*: the number of units sold in each week

Brand 1 and 2 are the most popular beer brands with similar weekly unit sales and high variation from week to week. Whereas brand 3 has a much more consistent but lower sales volume. The retail sales price of each brand is similar and hovers between approximately \$4 and \\$5. At least a certain percentage of each brand is on 'display' each week with brand 1 generally having the largest percentage of stock keeping units on display. Beer brands are 'featured' much less frequently.

The SCAN*PRO model is sensitive to bias in the estimated parameters if the variables are endogenous. For example, the price coefficient may be biased if store managers set their prices based on the level of sales of the product. If this is the case an instrumental variable approach can be taken using wholesale prices instead which are not controlled by the manager.

The potential endogeneity problem will be investigated later in the analysis if required.

All three brands exhibit a significant seasonal impact on unit sales. This will need to be incorporated into the regression model.

Data Preparation¶

Cleaning and transforming the data for modelling.

The SCAN*PRO model is a multiplicative model, however, the parameters can be log transformed to create a linear model which is easier to estimate.

Following the EDA, a series of new/transformed features will be added to the dataset to be used in the regression model. Subsets of these features will be chosen for the final regression model:

  1. A log transformation will be applied to each column so the model can be expressed as a linear function. Note that due to the presence of zero values, a log(x+1) transformation will be applied.
  2. Seasonal dummy variables will be added to account for the seasonality in the unit sales
  3. The 'FEATUREDBRAND*' columns will be converted into a binary variable as most of the values are zero

SCAN*PRO Regression¶

A regression model for each brand will be created to estimate the (log) unit sales the beer brand.

Train/validation¶

The target for each model will be the log_unit sales of the brand in question. The features for the model will include:

  • Seasonal dummy variables
  • 'FEATURED' as binary variable
  • log price
  • log display

The models will be first estimated using a training set and validated on a test set to indicate whether the SCAN*PRO model is a good fit for the data.

In [22]:
#create a list of months

binary_feature_cols = get_cols('^binary', data.columns)

Price

As expected the biggest effect on unit sales is the price of brand 1's product. As the price and target variable (unit sales) are both in log form, the coefficient of log_PRICEBRAND1 can be interpreted as meaning that if the price of brand 1 is reduced by 1%, unit sales will increase by 4.87%. Interestingly, brand 1's unit sales are also increased if the price of brand 3 is reduced, however, this is to a much lesser extent. If brand 2's price is decreased by 1%, unit sales of brand 1 are reduced by 1.40%. This makes sense as according to the unit sale plots of brand 1 and 2, they are selling in approximately the same volumes and are as popular as each other, so there might be a propensity for consumers to switch brand depending on price changes.

display

Only log_display_brand1 is statistically significant for the display variables. Therefore, whether brand 2 or 3 are on display has no effect on the unit sales of brand 1. The display variable is expressed as a percentage of stock keeping units (SKUs), therefore the coefficient of 0.67 for log_display_brand1 can be interpreted as meaning that if the percentage of SKUs on display of brand 1 are increased by 1% (note this is not the same as an increase in SKU by 1 percentage point) then the unit sales can be expected to increase by 0.67%.

Feature

Only binary_FEATUREBRAND1 is statistically significant for the FEATURE variables. The magnitude of the coefficient is 0.0939. As this is a binary variable and the target column was created using a log(x+1) transformation, the coefficient value is actually interpreted as being $e^{coefficient}$ i.e. $e^{0.0939}$ = 1.0984. This means that if the brand 1 is featured in a particular week (i.e. binary_FEATUREBRAND1 = 1), then unit sales can be expected to increase by 9.84%.

Price

The coefficient of log_PRICEBRAND3 can be interpreted as meaning that if the price of brand 3 is reduced by 1%, unit sales will increase by 6.14%.

display

log_display_brand3 has a coefficient of -0.4286 which is statistically significant, however, there is a relatively large error boundary which reaches an upper level of -0.017. This suggests that displaying more stock keeping units of brand 3 actually decreases the unit sales. The coefficient for log_display_brand2 shows that if more of brand 2 is displayed unit sales of brand 3 will increase.

Feature

Once again, none of the 'FEATURE' variables are statistically significant in the regression model for brand 3 unit sales. The binary_FEATUREBRAND3 coefficient is 0.1231 with a p value of 0.237. Even though the confidence in this coefficient is low and we cannot reject the null hypothesis, it would imply that if brand 3 is featured it would increase unit sales by 13.1% ($e^{0.1231)$ = 1.1310).
